description.value: Beads and pebble: the string consists of one long barrel bead of bone, a mottled green and white pebble, possibly diorite, and twenty-two long convex bicone cornelian beads. The cornelian beads are mostly very pale, almost colourless, a characteristic of cornelians used during the Old Kingdom. Their borings are wide, a further distinctive feature of Old Kingdom manufacture.

description.value: A string composed of spherical, oblate, long truncated convex bicone and five lenticular beads, all of amethyst, and a single long truncated convex bicone bead of cornelian. One of the lenticular beads has a neck at both ends and both of its faces are engraved along the edges with four rough lines in a diamond shape. The other lenticular beads consist of one flattened standard convex bicone, two flattened ellipsoids and one flattened long truncated convex bicone.

description.value: Collection of gold beads in various amuletic shapes: the five wallet beads are made in two halves: the join can be seen around the edge. They are hollow and have a double row of notching chased on the outer rim. The two holes at each end show they were part of a double-stringed girdle. They seem to be derived from 'Cowrie'-shells, which were popular as beads for girdles during the Middle Kingdom, although the type of shell cannot be identified with certainty by naturalists. Certainly it is much more likely to be a stylised shell than a wallet. The eight trussed-duck beads were also made in two halves. The ducks are depicted lying flat, with their heads twisted around over their backs. The details of eye, beak, wing- and tail-feathers have been roughly chased; five have spots on their under-bellies, while the remainder are plain. The snake's head bead is made in two halves; the details of eyes, spots on the back of the head and the pattern on the windpipe are chased. The lotus-flower bead consists of two cups on stems which are joined at the base. The cup part is made of a bowl decorated with sepals; added at the top is a collar with chased decoration imitating four rings. The two stems are joined together with solder of a different colour from that of the gold of the rest of the piece.

description.value: Amuletic string: apart from the large 'Petunculus' shell and a single damaged cylinder of green glazed steatite, the beads and amulets are of glazed composition. The three moulded beads with spiral decoration are of blue-green glazed composition. The long cylindrical beads of uneven lengths and roughly broken at the ends are blue, green and dark-purple. There are two green oblate beads, a single dark-green very long truncated convex bicone and a dark-green barrel. The two amulets, one of green glazed composition, the other of blue with a knob of green, are virtually unidentifiable.

description.value: 13 beads of different shapes and materials. A: Barrel-shaped glass bead, broken at one end, made of dark blue glass with a a white glass filament running around the body in a spiral shape.  B: Two small roughly spherical beads made of glass, one of them dark blue the other with a white corrosion layer. C: Large disc-bead with a small perforation and a sharp edge, made of some sort of faience in a vivid turquoise colour. D: Very small bead in a flat disc-shape, with small protruding parts creating a flower pattern. Made of turquoise faience. E: One flattened spherical bead made of greenish glass. F: One cylindrical bead made of red faience. One shallow groove running along the body.  G: Two small disc-shaped beads made of turquoise faience, one of them slightly smaller. H: Four cylindrical segmented beads made of turquoise faience.

description.value: Amuletic string: composed of small bright-blue glass disc beads, one blue glazed composition disc bead and thirty-one gold vase-shaped beads. The glass beads are almost certainly New Kingdom in date, but the vase-shaped beads are probably Middle Kingdom. The latter are made in three parts: the neck is a tube of sheet gold, the body is made in two parts, upper and lower, and the lip is a separate piece. The tube of the neck fits inside the upper half of the bowl. The lip is formed from a disc with a hole in the middle, shaped into a small funnel which is pushed into the top of the neck. The base of each vase has a hole in it which has been punched through from the inside, leaving a slight burr. The vase-shaped beads are graded in size: the largest are in the centre of the string, while the smallest ones, are at the ends.

description.value: A string of three 'Purpura' shells, two very badly damaged, ten 'Nerita' shells, three bone barrel beads and six pendants of various materials. Two of the bone beads are long barrels and the other is a standard barrel. The black limestone pendant is roughly oblong in shape and all its surfaces are decorated with incised cross-hatching. The flat, semicircular pendant with off-centre boring is of red porphyry. The drop pendant, flat on upper and lower surfaces, of black and white diorite is 2.4cm long. The small bone tooth-shaped pendant, now mottled brown in colour, is concave on one face and convex on the other.  The two remaining pendants are pebbles: one, of quartz, has pink and white banding, a flat top edge and a rounded lower one; the other pebble pendant of agate has brown and white banding and is roughly triangular in section.

description.value: 13 beads of different shape and material and one spacer. A: Spacer-bead made of red faience, six segments preserved, very eroded on all sides, parts chipped off. B: Bead in an elongated shape with a thickened end, the other end is broken off. Made of a paste material, faience or frit (?) in a greyish-bluish colour. C: Complete cylindrical bead made of white faience, with rounded edges at the end. D: Three flattened spherical beads made of well glazed shiny faience in a pearlescent colour. Two slightly smaller than the third one. E: One cylindrical segmented bead, three segments preserved, one broken off though, made of faience, no colour preserved. F: Seven disc-shaped beads in slightly varying sizes, the colour differs from blue to light green to whitish.

description.value: Five beads of different shape and material and a fragment of an amulet. A: Floral cone-bead made of turquoise faience, relatively long. B: Three disc-shaped beads made of ostrich eggshell. One slightly smaller than the other two. C: One flattened sphere bead made of white faience. D: Small fragment of an amulet, made of a pinkish glazed stone (?), only the lug and a small part of the actual amulet are preserved, difficult to define, maybe part of a floral element or head with hair? The perforation is askew and very thin at the rear.

description.value: 30 beads of different shapes and materials. A: One flattened sphere bead made of blue glass with white lines.  B: Bead made of turquoise glaze in the shape of a flat flower cone. The base is flat, almost all edges are chipped of. C: Cylindrical bead with rounded edges, made of light green faience. D: Flattened spherical bead made of light green faience. E: Two ring beads made of white faience.  F: One bead made of white stone in a biconical shape, one end partly broken off. G: Five beads in a disc shape with circumferential notches along the outer face, made of light green faience. Two of them glued together. H: One small cylindrical segmented bead made of white faience, three segments preserved. I: Small biconical bead made of red jasper. J: Five disc-shaped beads made of ostrich eggshell and one made of shell. K: 12 disc-shaped beads made of faience in different colours from white and yellow to blue and turquoise.

description.value: Amuletic necklace: the frog amulet, two shell-shaped beads, one long barrel and one long cylinder are of semi-translucent pale greenish-grey serpentine; the broken, long cylinder is of opaque green-grey steatite. Long cylindrical beads and a single disc are of green and blue glazed composition. The short cylindrical and remaining disc beads are of green feldspar, except for one short cylinder and two disc beads of pink limestone. The string is completed by two barrels and one long cylinder of Egyptian blue and a small 'Conus' shell.

legal.credit_line: © The Trustees of the British Museum

description.value: Four copper beads in the form of rings: one is described by the excavators as 'of thin metal ribbon wound up spirally to form a ring'; the shape is Brunton's 86W3. The three others are quite different: 'a thick strip of copper, rectangular in section, was bent round in a flat circle till the ends touched, thus forming a ring.' The first method is the usual one of Predynastic times; the second is apparently new.

description.value: Amuletic string: the electrum eye amulet is not a wedjat but the hieroglyphic sign of an eye. There are three gold cylinder disc beads and three gold barrel beads, the latter made of foil. The black material showing in the join of one bead is not core material but apparently the same resinous compound which covers some of the other beads. The gold spiral bead is made from a flat piece of gold wire twisted into seven coils with space between each twist. There are two long truncated convex bicones and a long, thin cylinder, all of green feldspar. The cornelian beads consist of one long barrel, three short barrels and two cylinders. A single long cylinder and eight short cylinders and discs, all of turquoise, complete the string.

description.value: beads made of different materials A: Poppy seed pendant made of a slightly transparent carnelian, the top end is slightly chipped off and the section of the body is rather oval than round. B: two fragments of cylindrical segmented beads made of white eroded faience. One of them is only half preserved, the other one shows three segments.  C: two spherical beads made of faience, one of them white, the other light green. D: one small extended sphere bead made of blue faience. E: three disc-shaped beads made of light green to turquoise faience. F: one disc-shaped bead made of ostrich eggshell

description.value: Beads made in different shapes and materials. A: 7 flattened spherical beads with a slightly higher part in the middle, made of turquoise. B: Conical flower bead made of red faience, flattened at the base and textured at the upper side.  C: One larger disc-shaped bead made of turquoise faience. D: One cylindrical bead made of light blue faience, eroded to white. E: One disc-shaped bead with deep notches at the outer face, made of light green faience. F: Two ovoid beads, broken into several fragment, probably made of glass, slightly corroded now. G: Three segmented cylindrical beads, only two or three segments preserved, one made of red faience, the others in white faience. H: Two short cylindrical beads made of faience. I: One ring-shaped bead made of glass? or similar paste, grey with a pearlescent layer. J: One ring-shaped bead made of gold.
